author: Lian Pin_Koh;
title: A drone's-eye view of conservation

aws-transcripts.transcript: When we think of Nepal, we tend to think of the snow capped mountains of the Himalayas, the crystal clear still waters of its Alpine lakes or the huge expense of its grasslands. What some of us might not realize is there in the Himalayan foothills, where the climate is much warmer and the landscape much greener, there leave a great diversity of wildlife, including the one horned rhinoceros, the Asian elephant and the bangle tiger. Unfortunately, these animals under constant threat from poaches who hunt and kill them for their body parts. To stop the killing of these animals, battalions of soldiers and rangers are sent to protect Nepal's national parks. But that is not an easy task because these soldiers have to patrol thousands of hectares of forest on foot or elephant backs. It is also risky for these soldiers when they get into gunfights with poachers, and therefore Nepal is always looking for new ways to help with protecting the forests and wildlife. Recently, Nepal a quiet, a new tool in the fight against wildlife crime, and these are drones or, more specifically, conservation drones. For about a year now, my colleagues and I have been building drones for Nepal and training the park protection personnel on the use of these drones. Not only does the drone give you a bird's eye view off the landscape, but it also allows you to capture detailed, high resolution images of objects on the ground. This, for example, is a pair off rhinoceros taking a cooling bath on the hot summer day in the lowlands off Nepal. We believe that drones have tremendous potential not only for combating while life crime, but also for monitoring the health of these wildlife populations. So what is the drone? Well, the kind of drone I'm talking about is simply a model aircraft fitted with an autopilot system. And this auto pilot unit contains a tiny computer, a GPS, a compass, a barometric altimeter and a few other sensors. Now a drone like this is meant to carry a useful payload, such as a video camera or a photographic camera. It also requires a software that allows the user to program a mission to tell the drone where to go. The people I talked to often surprised when they hear that these are the only four components that make a conservation drone.
